-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Find the value of \(abc\) given the positive reals \(a(b+c)=152,\; b(c+a)=162,\; c(a+b)=170.\) 2. [Key Idea] Each equation is the sum of two pairwise products; solving for the three products \(ab,\;bc,\;ca\) lets us obtain \((abc)^2\). 3. [Proof] Let \(x=ab,\; y=bc,\; z=ca.\) The three equations become (1) \(x+z=152\) (2) \(x+y=162\) (3) \(y+z=170\) Solve the linear system: • From (2) – (1): \(y-z=10\) • With (3): \(y+z=170\) Add: \(2y=180\Rightarrow y=90\); hence \(z=80\). Substitute in (2): \(x+90=162\Rightarrow x=72\). Thus \(ab=72,\; bc=90,\; ca=80.\) Now \((abc)^2=(ab)(bc)(ca)=72\cdot90\cdot80=518{,}400\) \(\Longrightarrow\ abc=\sqrt{518{,}400}=720\) (positive root). 4. [Conclusion] The product is \(abc = 720\) (choice D).
